{"id":"1808.08407","submitter":"Mathew Joseph","authors":"Partha Dey, Mathew Joseph, Ron Peled","title":"Longest increasing path within the critical strip","comments":"29 pages, 7 figures. A preliminary version of this paper has been\n  available on the first author's website since December 2015","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A Poisson point process of unit intensity is placed in the square $[0,n]^2$.\nAn increasing path is a curve connecting $(0,0)$ with $(n,n)$ which is\nnon-decreasing in each coordinate. Its length is the number of points of the\nPoisson process which it passes through. Baik, Deift and Johansson proved that\nthe maximal length of an increasing path has expectation\n$2n-n^{1/3}(c_1+o(1))$, variance $n^{2/3}(c_2+o(1))$ and that it converges to\nthe Tracy-Widom distribution after suitable scaling. Johansson further showed\nthat all maximal paths have a displacement of $n^{\\frac23+o(1)}$ from the\ndiagonal with probability tending to one as $n\\to \\infty$. Here we prove that\nthe maximal length of an increasing path restricted to lie within a strip of\nwidth $n^{\\gamma}, \\gamma<\\frac23$, around the diagonal has expectation\n$2n-n^{1-\\gamma+o(1)}$, variance $n^{1 - \\frac{\\gamma}{2}+o(1)}$ and that it\nconverges to the Gaussian distribution after suitable scaling.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 25 Aug 2018 10:57:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-08-28"}
